
Mem Multi-Port Memory (ports)
The mem component can expose multiple independent access ports to the same physical memory array.
This allows multiple readers and writers to access the same memory during the same simulation step.
Common uses:
• Von Neumann CPUs (instruction fetch + data access)
• Shared lookup tables
• DMA demonstrations
• Multiple processors sharing memory
• CPU + peripheral accessing the same RAM

───

Syntax
Single-port memory (default):
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
:

Equivalent to:
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
  ports: 1
:


───

Dual-port memory:
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
  ports: 2
:


───

Triple-port memory:
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
  ports: 3
:


───

Port Naming
Port 1 uses the original names:
text
adr
data
write
get

Additional ports use a numeric prefix:
text
2adr
2data
2write
2get

3adr
3data
3write
3get

...


───

Port 1
Read:
text
.ram:{
  adr = 0010
}

8wire x = .ram:get


───

Write:
text
.ram:{
  adr = 0010
  data = 10101010
  write = 1
}


───

Port 2
Read:
text
.ram:{
  2adr = 0100
}

8wire y = .ram:2get


───

Write:
text
.ram:{
  2adr = 0100
  2data = 11110000
  2write = 1
}


───

Simultaneous Reads
Multiple ports may read simultaneously.
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
  ports: 2
:

text
.ram:{
  adr  = 0001
  2adr = 0010
}

8wire a = .ram:get
8wire b = .ram:2get

Both values are read during the same propagation step.

───

Simultaneous Read + Write
Allowed.
text
.ram:{
  adr = 0001
}

.ram:{
  2adr = 0100
  2data = 11110000
  2write = 1
}

Port 1 reads while port 2 writes.

───

Dual-Port CPU Example
Instruction fetch and data access simultaneously.
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
  ports: 2
:

Instruction port:
text
.ram:{
  adr = pc
}

8wire opcode =
.ram:get

Data port:
text
.ram:{
  2adr = operandAddress
}

8wire value =
.ram:2get

Both accesses happen during the same simulation step.

───

Shared CPU + DMA Example
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
  ports: 2
:

CPU:
text
.ram:{
  adr = cpuAddress
}

DMA:
text
.ram:{
  2adr = dmaAddress
}

CPU and DMA access the same RAM independently.

───

Multi-Word Writes
All ports support the same multi-word write behavior.
Example:
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 16
  ports: 2
:

text
.ram:{
  2adr = 0000
  2data = 1111000011110000
  2write = 1
}

Result:
text
address 0 = 11110000
address 1 = 11110000


───

Read Semantics
Reads are combinational.
text
.ram:{
  adr = 0100
}

8wire x =
.ram:get

returns the current value stored at address 4.

───

Write Semantics
Writes occur during the memory commit phase.
If multiple writes occur during the same simulation step, collision rules apply.

───

Write Collision
Two ports writing to the same address during the same simulation step is illegal.
Example:
text
.ram:{
  adr = 0010
  data = ^AA
  write = 1
}

.ram:{
  2adr = 0010
  2data = ^55
  2write = 1
}

Error:
text
Memory write collision at address 2

Memory contents remain unchanged.

───

Port Out Of Range
Using a port that does not exist is an error.
Example:
text
comp [mem] .ram:
  depth: 8
  length: 256
  ports: 2
:

text
.ram:{
  3adr = 0001
}

Error:
text
Memory port 3 does not exist


───

Address Width Validation
Each port uses the same address width.
Example:
text
length: 256

requires:
text
8-bit addresses

for:
text
adr
2adr
3adr
...

Address width mismatches produce the same errors as single-port memories.

